\begin_layout Section

Cluster based splitting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "CML"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

This first method transposes the dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $ D $
\end_inset

 into a dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $ D^T $
\end_inset

 where every attribute 
\begin_inset Formula $ A = X \cup L $
\end_inset

 becomes a instance of 
\begin_inset Formula $ D^T $
\end_inset

. In the next step a cluster algorithm is applied to the dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $ D^T $
\end_inset

, resulting in clusters representing attributes of 
\begin_inset Formula $ D $
\end_inset

. Because label values are binary, in contrast to the features which can be numeric values, a preprocessing step normalizes all values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In the resulting clusters, features and labels which are similar are combined. In respect to the method this will be a distance metric as used by Hierarchical Clustering and k-means or a probability distribution as used by EM. Therefore the clusters are grouped by attributes showing a similarity among the instances. These attributes have a higher dependence in-between the cluster than the to the rest of data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Those attributes can be split into features and labels, forming subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $ D_{1..n} \subset D $
\end_inset

 of the complete dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $ D $
\end_inset

. On each of those subsets a multi-label learner can be trained and predictions for the subsets of labels are composed together to gain a prediction for the entire labelset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

Feature- and Cluster based Splitting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "FCML"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

As the first method is based on the pure attribute values in the data, it can not qualify attributes in respect to a label. It can only group attributes sharing common values among the instances, but not on its relevance to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

To overcome this problem a second method has been developed which takes into account the relevance of features in respect to the labels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

For every label 
\begin_inset Formula $ Y \in L $
\end_inset

 of the dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $ D $
\end_inset

 a feature selection is performed as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chapter:FeatureSelection"

\end_inset

. This results in a new matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $ D_{FS}=(x_{ij})_{i=1..l,j=1..m} $
\end_inset

 where every row 
\begin_inset Formula $ i $
\end_inset

 represents a label, every column 
\begin_inset Formula $ j $
\end_inset

 represents a attribute (features and labels) and 
\begin_inset Formula $ x_{ij} $
\end_inset

 is the score computed by the feature selection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Subsequent a clustering is applied. Note that instances in 
\begin_inset Formula $ D_{FS} $
\end_inset

 represent labels of 
\begin_inset Formula $ D $
\end_inset

, so every cluster is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $ L $
\end_inset

. To add features the feature selection scores are used. For every instance 
\begin_inset Formula $ i $
\end_inset

 of a cluster 
\begin_inset Formula $ c $
\end_inset

 every attribute 
\begin_inset Formula $ X_j $
\end_inset

 represents the score of attribute 
\begin_inset Formula $ X_j $
\end_inset

 in respect to the label 
\begin_inset Formula $ Y_i \in L $
\end_inset

. If this score exceeds a threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $ X_j $
\end_inset

 will be added to the current group. As labels will be grouped by clustering they are ignored in this step.
\end_layout

